<subSubSection pageNumber="360" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="360">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="360">Note:</emphasis>
Hitchcock (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="360">Contr. U. S. Natl. Herb.</emphasis>
12: 122. 1908) stated that no type was extant. Baum (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="360">Canad. J. Bot.</emphasis>
45: 1849. 1967) referred to a specimen at S, annotated by Linnaeus &quot;H. U. 4 e semine Canadensi&quot; (sheet 40.9), as the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“holotype”">
&quot;
<typeStatus>holotype</typeStatus>
&quot;
</normalizedToken>
, with sheet 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“93.10”">&quot;93.10&quot;</normalizedToken>
at LINN (actually 93.12), annotated on the verso by Linnaeus with &quot;e semine canaden.&quot;, an 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“isotype”">
&quot;
<typeStatus>isotype</typeStatus>
&quot;
</normalizedToken>
. However, McNeill (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="360">Taxon</emphasis>
25: 612-613. 1976) convincingly argued that 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Baum’s">Baum's</normalizedToken>
typification was unacceptable because the specimens (LINN 93.10, 93.12 &amp; S 40.9) conflict with 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
diagnosis and, in the absence of any relevant original material, he designated a 
<typeStatus>neotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
